text: This movie appears to be pointless. If this movie has no relationship to the cartoon and is presumably based on the non-Disney folklore instead, then it has no reason to 'reference' the cartoon by playing the song Reflection except to dupe the less cognitively-inclined who love the cartoon to want to see it.   This also better be PG-13 as that would suit a movie with realistic portrayal of war and violence, otherwise this movie only serves to appease those who wanted Mulan to be more 'serious' while at the same time taming it down to make it child-friendly since it has what should be a non-existent connection to a PG animated film. The movie has no singing, Mushu and presumably the cricket, and the characters are completely different, therefore any alluding to the cartoon is pointless and just exists for artistic merit-less commercial purposes.

text: Okay here is my big problem. The story original and Disney are great, it's symbolic and powerful. But the point of Mulan is that she isn't the most beautiful, she is boyish. It's why she could pass as a soldier. She cuts her hair because that's what warriors did, not because it looked good, she did it to metaphorically cut off her past life.  This makes Mulan look like a frilly girly character even in armour. You can just tell that it's a female, and she would also never let her hair out for dramatic effect. It would show that she is a woman and it's really ineffective in a fight.  Mulan isn't a girly girl, and she isn't defined by beauty standards of her time or ours, she is a warrior. She puts her life at risk for others, not just a pretty face.  For me I honestly hate what they did with her character. I might not be Asian but I know when a story is being ruined by so called "awareness". If you think this is epic because it's aware of culture, then you should not be up for other Disney remakes, especially the Little Mermaid that's a DANISH story. If Disney wants to be so hip they should remake Snow White in a way that doesn't make her seem like some 1950 housewife. Or heres a better idea. COME UP WITH ORIGINAL STORIES!

text: To those who wonder what she said at the end: Hua Mulan translates to 'forest orchid'- Hua=flower Mu=wood Lan=Orchid. So- forest orchid flower is Mulan's meaning. I think it adds allot of depth to her character because she's a supposedly delicate flower amongst great trees and yet she grows and blossoms and survives in that environment when no one expected her to. She's an outsider, a special one, a survivor against all odds. That's a beautiful twist, don't you think...?

text: Personally,  this looks so different from the original and I'm here for it. If I wanted to see them remake everything just like the original, I'd just watch the original. Imho, this is what they should do with live action remakes - remake and reinterpret them. Bring something new to the table.  That's worth spending time and money on.  The live action Disney remakes that are basically the same as the original movies - but with less heart and soul - really bother me. So yay for no singing! Yay for no talking animal sidekicks! The original is still amazing and delightful and is there for all of that. This can be something new and different, and that's okay!

text: Growing up with a part Chinese family, I was so proud of my heritage but there weren’t many things that I could, as a child, say belonged to my culture until I found Mulan. Now growing up I understand the first movies inconsistencies with Chinese traditions and customs and while it still remains so close to my heart, I can understand that a lot of it was quite disrespectful. This film looks so beautiful and the trailer alone made me cry. I’m so glad that a lot more effort to be culturally accurate was put into this movie and hopefully it lives up to expectations!!

text: I like that this is slightly different than the original. The original is undeniably a classic. A remake of it in live action would probably never do it justice. The humor and the comedy (aka Mushu and the songs) really made that movie special. But I think this movie is trying to highlight the gravity of Mulan, which the original animation lacked, thus elevating the emotions of honor and sacrifice and all the things we love about Mulan in the first place. Plus, its not like they are scrapping all of the songs of the old movie (aka when they started playing Reflection, i'm with all of  you guys on the bawling)  I am definitely super excited to see this! (It's showing the day before my birthday next year!)

I strongly neoliberals that this isn’t a live action remake but a live action telling of the ORIGINAL tale. Or, well, the romantic version. Instead of Fa Mulan, Disney’s adaptation, you have Hua Mulan, from the original tale.  In that tale she had a little sister, but i don’t recall her being blood related, and there was no mushu or grandma or handsome warrior to steal her heart.  However, since it’s Disney, there won’t be that tragic ending.   Spoiler!!    Her father died. Her mom remarried. And she killed herself so not to become a concubine.

text: La Historia de la Geisha Ana .  Una Geisha multifacetica recluida en su casa, con habilidades marciales interior, Se encuentra varios días recluida, preparando una estrategia personal de guerra y mecanismos de Autodefensas..  Por las noches se da un baño alquimista con componentes de agua marina, flores, sales de Guindas, con toque de vainilla y otro toque de perfume con esencia divina . Ese baño se lo da de madrugada, con una copa  preparada como ouja, postura de equilibrio siete chackras y un viaje Nocturno Astral para consultas diarias con Allah..  Camina por las tardes a ver la ley de sincronicidad impuesta, bastante vulgar hoy, y muy vistosa cuando es natural o prepara por Angélica con ayuda Soviética..  Realiza cada noche una consulta a su Tarot de Marsella, bebé una copa de vino..  La Geisha Ana, divide su tiempo en lectura, oraciones con Suras, comparte sus revelaciones y visiones como denuncias y alertas urgentes..Pinta cuadros, investiga el pasado, presente y futuro.. Se realiza maquillajes Samurái para equilibrar el Karma entre un mundo antiguo Samurái y de Geishas a futuro..  Su historia se cuenta como leyenda antigua en el Jardín Botánico de Torremolinos, donde varias esculturas enseñan de manos Samurái, su rebeldía pasada, su lucha constante por la Justicia Universal e igualdad humana..  En el Parque de la Batería, hay un punto energético del sexto chakra o tercer ojo, si lo visitas una vez en la vida puedes aprovechar su influencia Astral.. En el Parque de la Batería hay un monumento a dos Ángeles caídos de guerra por traición Samurái antigua, Demián y Angélica..  En esta reencarnación han tropezado con la misma piedra, levantándose con más fuerza interior y mejorando su estrategia de Guerra.   La Geisha Ana, posee en sus manos el pozo de los deseos, convierte el agua en agua de manantial divina pura, con conocimientos Esotéricos, revelaciones, y curas de enfermedades emocionales..  La Geisha Ana, pinta cuadros en casa y escribe cuentos, prepara rituales para cada visita de algún caído o perseguido, llamado Hospitium..  La Geisha Ana no está en penitencia al ser humano, esta en penitencia a Allah.. No permite que nadie la toque ni se acerque a su morada, donde reflexiona hasta finalizado su entrenamiento Militar Samurái y evolución Esotérica.. Está de castidad permanente muestras dure en entrenamiento, pueden los invitados al Hospitium dormir en casa, beber de su agua, y comer en su mesa, pero no pueden ni deben dirigirle la palabra, ni mirarla a los ojos..  Convive con Samurái que aprendieron las reglas de convivencia básicas con un Geisha.. Es bombardeada a diario en su casa, por detractores, invasores, falsos clarividentes y falsas Geishas.. Iblis hoy ha dado aire en su misión, computado por tres a partir de mañana..  Nieves es su Tutora, se encarga de sus gestiones y representación judicial y cortés marciales.  Ella tiene una petición oficial por preparación y formación permanente y recuperación del verano de tres meses, renovables a más . Pendiente de resolución por parte del Ayuntamiento de Torremolinos para que Nieves se haga cargo de sus compromisos y Llamados .  Hoy recibió como hace tres noches la visita de su hilo Rosa o Alma gemela según la carta Natal Samurái, llamado Ali, pueden intercambiar opiniones a través de Telepatía pero sin miradas ni acercamientos.. No significa que lleguen a consumar la relación por la dificultad del mundo y la persecución a ambos . Las Geishas nunca se casan, ni los Samurái, mantienen un amor eterno Unido por algún fondo común o compartiendo gastos, tareas, responsabilidades de todo tipo .  En una entrevista Samurái le pregunté al Consejo: Como puedo cortar los hilos rojos atados y quedarme con el mío Rosa.  Respuesta: nunca lo conseguirás, aunque avances..Las Geishas nunca se mezclan con los Samurái, Ali es Samurái.. Te espera un profeta Judío, aunque no pertenezca a esa religión, está unido y ha nacido al Judaísmo..  Tu padrino Samurái  Madrina Samurái: Te vamos a instruir en arte del deber sin mezclarnos,  Sabemos que ésta, es tu Tierra Geisha por as señales del Botánico,  Aquí somos mayoría, sois solo tres Geishas en extinción..( Celia., Jazmín de Arabia y Tú) Aquí no pueden intimidar con Samurái, se mantienen las formas, un diálogo discreto y básico, cuando recibas un obsequio o tu hija, ni sonrisas ni Gracias.. La distancia es la base de una buena convivencia . En las calles y casa, serán unas señoras intocables, si alguien se atreve, lo castraremos en público .sin previo aviso.. Solo Hola y Adiós.  Maestra Samurái

text: Stop asking for Mushu! He's not supposed to be there! Stop asking for Li Shang! He's not supposed to be there either! The ONLY thing Disney's animated version of Mulan has in common with the original source material is that she took up her father's arms to fight in a war(for 10 years straight if I might add). If you all can get over your nostalgia maybe you can actually go and read the original Ballad of Mulan which is over 1500 years old and learn a thing or two.  For one I'm glad that they chose to make it more appealing to Chinese audiences. It's part of our literature and culture, we literally memorize and recite WORD FOR WORD the verses to her Ballad in grade school and middle school! You're all telling me you want a copy and paste of the animated version? Yeah look what happened to Beauty and the Beast I'm sure that'll work out just great! Also on that note lets completely disregard what the dragon represents in Chinese culture (the emperor himself) and make him comedy relief by recasting Eddie Murphey JUST to satisfy your nostalgic whims! A Phoenix is much better fit for her either way, it is a symbol of femininity and grace.  You want a sing-a-long? Go watch Frozen. You want a Disney princess romance? Go watch Tangled. But you probably shouldn't criticize the "source material" if you have never even read the original and if you haven't been paying close attention its not the Disney animated version.

text: To all the people asking about why this movie is so different, it's because they're basing off the original story of Hua Mulan. In the original story there is no Mushu or a love interest like Shang. The Phoenix is Mushu as the Phoenix represents a queen while a dragon represents a king which is not what Mulan is. However in the original she didn't have to pretend to be a man so they kept that part in there.

text: This is better than the teaser trailer that came out a while back, but it still misses the mark of what made the original so special. The only supernatural element of the original was the existence of the ancestors' spirits and guardian spirits. That's it. Everything else was just real people thrust into war. I hate the mythology being forced into this, because it didn't come up in the original. Leave it to Pixar to make a movie about ancient Chinese mythology. Don't shove extra unnecessary supernatural stuff in an otherwise simple story.  Another thing they missed about what drew people into the classic cartoon version is who Mulan is at her core. The original villain and his army were just an unstoppable force, brutal and vicious. They weren't beaten by Mulan because she was strong and well trained. She beat them because she was clever and used what she had at her disposal to gain the upper hand. She's not as strong as a man, and never could be. So she had to use her wits to get out of danger and help defeat the enemy.

text: I love the original Mulan movie because it was one of the first times I saw my race portrayed in media: when I finally saw an Asian on a large platform in a positive light. I loved her character and the movie will always be one of my favorites. I was, and still am, so proud to be a Chinese American.  But the original was not hated, but not as loved by my parents in comparison to me. And it wasn’t until much later when I was told that the story is very different from its original history. They weren’t particularly in love with Mushu either, because, truth be told, he is a bit of a culturally offensive character. The original movie was amazing, but it wasn’t accurate.  This live action remake IS more accurate. Yes, there’s a witch, but she’s much more culturally appropriate and appreciative than Mushu is. She’s not being served as comic relief. I think this much more serious take on the movie is much needed: to inform today’s youth of a more realistic and true Mulan and the importance of her story. But also, to give the Chinese American youth a much more accurate role model and someone they physically look like, as the original did for me years ago.  I’m excited for this movie! And I hope people understand the significance and appreciate how this live action remake will actually be more realistic, in both a production and historical/cultural sense.

text: i understand this is your "childhood", mine too my brother and i watched Mulan day to night, but this is the change we need, and the change the story deserves. Mulan 2020 is not going to be the same as the original. That would've been useless. it is not a "remake" it is a "live action" portraying the story as it would be in *real life* you may not agree with any of these changes, but how long have you had your degree in filmmaking and directing? The directors know what theyre doing. they are learning from mistakes they made in the past, as Mulan had a few culturally insensitive things in it. And this story tells the struggle of a people who have no power gaining it. Women fighting to get rights. Taking such a strong topic that is still being fought for today, and making it lighthearted like a joke is inappropriate.  Please be open and support the movie. These changes are what will make the movie powerful. We have grown too adapted to the ignorant things we saw as a child.

This girl-though beautiful and talented, this isn't on her- is being written as some battle ready hero already, cool calm collected, dare I say even WRITTEN a little flat? text: Look, there is no doubt in my mind that I will love this movie. However, it still saddens me to see it lacking my favourite characters and the fun music.   In my opinion, anyone could make this version of Mulan, and people have before. But only Disney could remake the magic of the animated movies. I appreciate this more accurate version but, like... this is Disney movie, man. Disney is supposed to be (for the most part) fun and magical.   If this was made by any other company, it wouldn't bother me as much. But seeing as it is Disney making this, the child in me, who grew up loving Crickey and Mushu and singing along to the songs, is disappointed to see all that go.

text: I'm really happy that this movie will give acting opportunities to a lot more Asian Americans, but tonally it seems like a mess. The cartooney elements that fans pushed so hard to be included will clash heavily with the serious war tone the Chinese film company was going for lol.   Also, the main character seems strong, but not charismatic (in the trailers). and has perfect hair and makeup on the battlefield lol  what?    Perhaps it would have been better for a proper historical Mulan retelling that was separate from the Disney version. But I guess there would be funding issues etc. I feel like this movie is going to be a clash of cultures and wills, but I'm hoping for the best.  However, I love the inclusion of Gong Li as the witch, and the fact that Mulan still has a guardian ..... idk still hoping for the best!!!

text: I may become dramatic but this movie that I shouldn't stop myself from being bold. I was a taekwondo student in my young days in grade school, it makes me miss that part where I was strong but now I'm just here in my room, scared of judgement and still am. Dad stopped me from taking taekwondo classes because he doesn't want me to have bruises or mess up my face. Even though sparring could hurt, I never cared since it was a challenge for me. I just feel I want to step up and be able to live with independence, but at this point, I'm still young to leave this house.  My dream is to get out of this cage, learn things on my own and be myself again.

text: My thoughts on the Mulan remake are so mixed. On one hand the trailer looks awesome and I'm excited to see my favorite Disney film be remade and I can respect the devs wanting to respect the original story and Chinese culture, but on the other hand, Disney marketed this as a remake of the Disney Mulan so I'm disappointed that there will be no Shang or the songs. WHY LEAVE OUT THE SONGS?? I'm not upset about Mushu not being included because as Aladdin taught us, animal/sidekicks don't translate well in live action. Plus I can respect that they wanted to cut him out due to the Chinese hating him. But the other stuff? Like the classic scene where she cuts her hair (by the looks of the trailer, she won't cut it). Will Ling, Yao, Chien Po even be in it? I'm just kind of disappointed with how much they are changing...But who knows, maybe I will change my mind once the movie is out.

text: so, when I first heard about mulan having no mushu in it and varying from the „origianl“ movie I was so upset, as it is one of my favourite movies and mushu is my little favourite and I would have loved to see him in the remake BUT!! i had no clue how mulan was taken and changed from the original and how the chinese people were upset about it. I‘m sorry. I‘m glad disney is starting to be more sensitive to the different cultures and original stories. I didnt plan on watching the movie out of sheer spite bc of being so upset, but now I am growing and learning out of my emotions and my privilege. I think the part that makes mulan mulan, is not mushu or everything that mkes me love that movie so much, it‘s her being strong, fierce, loving. I always admired her for her power. I always saw her as a role model and I will continue to do so. I can‘t wait to watch the movie now. also I hope everyone who feels as upset as I did will find the ability and insight to really question your emotions and find out what is upsetting you. and then learning why they changed certain things. I‘m glad they did bc otherwise i would have probably never read into the original story of mulan. I‘m glad I learned and got more educated. also the movie looks fantastic, I‘m so happy I won‘t be missing out.

text: It's so silly how you're all crying around here complaining that they should have included Mushu because "they have a witch that turns into a bird so it's not even historically accurate anyway". You do know that legends and folklore are not the same thing as History... Riiiiiiiiiiiiiiight? So yeah, they're giving you Chinese folklore with a phoenix and a "witch" woman who can shapeshift (who most likely is inspired in another figure from Chinese folklore). It checks out, sorry. This move will not and was never going to be based on History, it's based on a LEGEND, the song of Hua Mulan. So "historical accuracy" is not a thing to worry about here 🤦🏻‍♀️  Chinese legends are pretty fucking dope. If they played their cards right, this movie will be very entertaining. Just get over it 😂. Aren't you tired of going to watch the same exact thing frame for frame at the cinema? Just rewatch the cartoon and let others enjoy some semblance of variety.

text: Facts about this film: its more based on the historical legend of Mulan. Not the Disney musical. The ballad of Hua Mulan.   You won't find the added in Disney comic relief characters you want, because this isn't a comic relief movie.   Shang doesn't exist. He was made up by Disney and not in the original story. So you won't find him.   No, this isn't just another live action remake. It's something new. No use getting offended that Disney's finally righting their wrongs and telling the real story.     The lead actress was reportedly forced to say what she did regarding Chinese police by the government of China. So it's not fair to punish her and the many, many people who worked on this film for something that wasn't her free will.

text: I’m actually in favor of this whole thing.  With the exception of The Jungle Book, every single Disney Remake has been a duplicate with little to no additions or reimaginings like a remake should. I don’t know where this movie is going to go, and I actually appreciate that.  I also found it quite nice that the music in the background is the song “Reflection” to pay respects to its predecessor. I’m curious (as I’m sure everybody else is too) about Mulan’s sister, and maybe then new villain will actually be interesting.      But press “F” to pay respects to Mushu as he will not be appearing in this film.

text: So just making sure I am getting this right. This not an adaptation for Disney's Mulan at all. 1) Mulan has a sister? 2) Who the hell is this witch transforming into a hawk or falcon 3) Grandma jokes not included 4) so no dragon even though dragons are Chinese mythology  5) so magic is a thing will there a be a scene with the ancestors bickering at each other or was magic only thrown in to add a Phoneix for some dumb reason, and a witch.  6)little brother and cricket are out the picture too. 7) even though reflections instrumental is playing in the bg, they are not trying to make this a musical, so I highly doubt she will sing. 8) Conclusion not a live remake of the Disney adaptation but just another new adaptation to the long-told story of Mulan. I love the use of an Asian cast, the Chinese dress attire and makeup, shoot even the weapon design are correct. I love the story of Mulan, watch different adaptations too, just dont like how Disney is really trying to sell this as a live remake of their original adaptation.

text: All these people who are not Chinese, asking where Mushu the dragon is, or why she didn't cut off her hair- PLEASE. I beg you to educate yourselves. The producers are TRYING to represent the real Chinese traditions and correlate the story to the traditional story of Mulan. The old Disney version was great but not accurate to Chinese cultures or the traditional story. Why would Mulan cut off her hair when Chinese soldiers often had long hair as men anyways??? Mushu the dragon was never apart of the real story and was added by Disney. I am not Chinese either but I am from Asia, please stop commanding excessive, unnecessary changes to the movie if you are not educated on the goal of this film or the traditions of China. They actually seem to be doing a great job by not whitewashing the movie and respecting the true roots of the movie. Thanks.

text: This movie looks horrible.      It looks like it has nothing of the original Mulan, it's gonna be some fourth-wave feminist bullshit with hyper action scenes and stupid magic plots. Like at 0:32 are those Huns RUNNING UP THE GREAT WALL? That's so much more cartoony than the Cartoon (Where they used grappling hooks). The original movie didn't need a witch/sorceress, Shan Yu was a big bad boi by himself, it's not like Mulan knew how to use magic and thus needed an antagonist with similar skills so the inclusion of that sorceress is just stupid.   Movies like this should never be made. It does nothing but patronize feminism and present a false image of female superiority. The original Mulan didn't patronize anything, but it was empowering and realistic (As much as a cartoon could be) as she was a woman in a misogynistic environment, forced to cut her hair and wrap her breasts in order to pass as male, and even then failing horribly at training at the beginning to the physical limitations of her gender and upbringing as a woman in Ancient China, both obstacles she got over by determination and relentless training. Even after all this, she was nearly executed by Shang for lying and only spared because she saved his life, quoting "A life for a life" before telling her to go home.  When she found out Shan Yu was still alive, everyone... EVERYONE even her own friends ignored her because she was a liar and 'just a woman' At least until Shan Yu actually kidnapped the Emperor.   Anyways, I'm done my rant. But this movie is gonna be garbage.
author: Mordred C

text: Like all great legends, this Disneyfied Americanized kiddie version is based on an ancient cultural tale, albeit Chinese this time because multiculturalism is the current pop trend. The main character's name was Hua Mulan and she's received the same  iconic status in Chinese literature and Chinese folk heroism as Paul Bunyan has in the U.S. IOWs, there are no rules when it comes to re-creating these legends because they're and myths, popular in the imagination but hard to pin down with recorded history.

text: The Ballad of Hua Mulan is set in the Northern Wei era (386–536). The poem starts with Mulan sitting worriedly at her loom, as one male from each family is called to serve in the army to defend the Tuoba realm from Rouran invaders. Her father is old and weak, and her younger brother is just a child, so she decides to take his place and bids farewell to her parents, who support her. She is already skilled in fighting, having been taught martial arts, sword fighting, and archery by the time she enlists in the army. After twelve years of fighting, the army returns and the warriors are rewarded. Mulan turns down an official post, and asks only for a camel to carry her home. She is greeted with joy by her family. Mulan dons her old clothes and meets her comrades, who are shocked that in the 12 years of their enlistment together, they did not realize that she was a woman       SO WHAT EXACTLY IS THIS LIVE ACTION THING BASED OFF OF?!

text: I honestly wish that since they're going the more serious route that instead of making it a "Disney remake" they should just make it a more so stand alone movie. Cause looking at it from stand alone it looks amazing, but looking at it from a live action remake it's completely different. Idk how to explain it, I guess what I mean is this just doesn't look like a Disney movie, it doesn't look like something Disney would make. I might actually watch this (even though I don't like live action Disney remakes) only because it doesn't really remind me of the original at all, it looks like a similar but different story and plot. Alot of stuff is different, main characters have been taken out, and it's no longer a musical. It's more realistic which is good, but it's not Disney if that makes sense. I get that that's what they were aiming for though. This will end up being one of the more successful live action remakes because this isn't really the "Mulan" we grew up watching, it's something new.

text: I just want to point out that Mushu was a spirit guide, and obviously we can’t see spirits unless they unveil themselves to us, so of course, he was not brought into the movie. Now, the witch/sorceress is actually a major part in the story because in ancient China there has been stories of great deities or gods/goddesses among them with unbelievable power. Witches were not uncommon, and some would be compared to medicine women and men, much like Native American Shamans. In the story, the general and the witch were of agreement that she would give him unbelievable power to aid him in his war with a price of course.

text: Ok it does seem like a good movie, but it’s just different from the Disney original. Main differences: -No Mushu -No lucky Cricket -No singing at all - No Li Shang (Mulan’s love interest)  - New love interest who was Mulans biggest rival and hated her when he thought she was a man, but when it’s revealed she’s a woman, immediately falls in love w her (I don’t rlly like that Li Shang was so much better) -Two daughters, Mulan has a sister -The enemies are not the Huns, it’s this evil witch. So basically, this film was made into a more serious adaptation that is more based on the actual Mulan myth, not Disney’s original. This is a film that would probably  be  rlly popular in Asia, as its a style that is rlly liked there. It is still good, I was just extremely disappointed it wasn’t like the original, but seeing as Disney made both movies, they obviously knew the plot, it’s just they original was a little twist from Disney, and this is more like the original myth.

text: While I understand the reason for leaving out Mushu because the character trivialized Chinese culture, I honestly wouldn’t have cared if they had decided to put him in anyway. China is the same country in which several movie goers and critics lambasted Black Panther ( a movie in which the setting was sub Saharan Africa) for being “Too black” 🤔. Sorry China, you can’t undermine and denigrate black culture then turn around and demand that your own be respected 🤷🏾‍♂️. Also, before anyone comments, I realize that Mulan is an ancient Chinese cultural tale, and Black Panther is a Marvel movie based off of a comic book. With that being said, I still don’t care. It’s all falls under the category of fiction, and Black Panther is still culturally significant for black people.

Bad enough the lead actress is anti-Hong Kong, but we don't get key elements from the first Disney telling, which I am going to miss. (No Li Shang, no Mushu, no Cricket. No original music score (Reflections without lyrics? LMFAO)... She apparently doesn't even cut her hair. Just?? What??) I absolutely understand that this is based on the real Mulan, but if I wanted to see that I would have watched the 2009 live adaptation. (Look it up... yeah, it existed already.) It's also a "fantasy" telling because you got witches that shape change and phoenixes. It's pretty stupid to say you can't throw in at least a baby dragon or a bi man if you have all that lmao
